<P>In <A href="/wiki/Argument" title="Argument">logical argument</A> and <A href="/wiki/Mathematical_proof" title="Mathematical proof">mathematical proof</A>, the <B>therefore sign</B> (∴) is generally used before a <A href="/wiki/Logical_consequence" title="Logical consequence">logical consequence</A>, such as the conclusion of a <A href="/wiki/Syllogism" title="Syllogism">syllogism</A>. The symbol consists of three dots placed in an upright triangle and is read <I>therefore</I>. It is encoded at <SPAN class="nowrap"><SPAN class="monospaced" style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">U+2234</SPAN></SPAN> <SPAN style="font-size:125%">∴</SPAN> <SPAN class="smallcaps" style="font-variant: small-caps; font-size: smaller;">therefore</SPAN> (HTML <CODE>&#8756;</CODE> <B>·</B>  <CODE>&there4;</CODE>). For common use in Microsoft Office hold the ALT key and type "8756". While it is not generally used in formal writing, it is used in <A href="/wiki/Mathematics" title="Mathematics">mathematics</A> and <A href="/wiki/Shorthand" title="Shorthand">shorthand</A>. It is complementary to <SPAN class="nowrap"><SPAN class="monospaced" style="font-family: monospace, monospace;">U+2235</SPAN></SPAN> <SPAN style="font-size:125%">∵</SPAN> <SPAN class="smallcaps" style="font-variant: small-caps; font-size: smaller;">because</SPAN> (HTML <CODE>&#8757;</CODE>).</P>

<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="History">History</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Therefore_sign&action=edit&section=1" title="Edit section: History">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>According to <A href="/wiki/Florian_Cajori" title="Florian Cajori">Cajori</A>, <I>A History of Mathematical Notations,</I> <A href="/wiki/Johann_Rahn" title="Johann Rahn">Johann Rahn</A> used both the <I>therefore</I> and <I>because</I> signs to mean "therefore"; in the German edition of <I>Teutsche Algebra</I> (1659) the <I>therefore</I> sign was prevalent with the modern meaning, but in the 1668 English edition Rahn used the <I>because</I> sign more often to mean "therefore".<SUP id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-1">[1]</A></SUP> Other authors in the eighteenth century also used three dots in a triangle shape to signify "therefore," but as with Rahn, there wasn't much in the way of consistency as to how the triangle was oriented; <I>because</I> with its current meaning appears to have originated in the nineteenth century. In this century, the three-dot notation for therefore became very rare in continental Europe, but it remains popular in the British Isles.<SUP id="cite_ref-Cajori2011_2-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Cajori2011-2">[2]</A></SUP></P>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Example_of_use">Example of use</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Therefore_sign&action=edit&section=2" title="Edit section: Example of use">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<P>Used in a <A href="/wiki/Syllogism" title="Syllogism">syllogism</A>:</P>
<DL>
<DD>All gods are immortal.</DD>
<DD><A href="/wiki/Zeus" title="Zeus">Zeus</A> is a god.</DD>
<DD>∴ Zeus is immortal.</DD>
</DL>
<DL>
<DD>x + 1 = 6</DD>
<DD>∴ x = 5</DD>
</DL>
<H2><SPAN class="mw-headline" id="Related_signs">Related signs</SPAN><SPAN class="mw-editsection"><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</SPAN><A href="/w/index.php?title=Therefore_sign&action=edit&section=3" title="Edit section: Related signs">edit</A><SPAN class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</SPAN></SPAN></H2>
<DIV class="thumb tleft">
<DIV class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><A href="/wiki/File:DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png" class="image"><IMG alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png/220px-DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png" width="220" height="156" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png/330px-DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png/440px-DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png 2x" data-file-width="1824" data-file-height="1290" /></A>
<DIV class="thumbcaption">
<DIV class="magnify"><A href="/wiki/File:DiplomeMa%C3%A7onnique1945.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></A></DIV>
A diploma from the Masonic <I><A href="/wiki/Grande_Loge_de_France" title="Grande Loge de France">Grande Loge de France</A></I> showing the symbol as a substitute for the dot of abbreviation.</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<P>The inverted form ∵, known as the <B>because sign</B>, is sometimes used as a <A href="/wiki/Shorthand" title="Shorthand">shorthand</A> form of "because". This is <A href="/wiki/Unicode" title="Unicode">Unicode</A> character U+2235.</P>
<P>The <I>therefore</I> sign is sometimes used as a substitute for an <A href="/wiki/Asterism_(typography)" title="Asterism (typography)">asterism</A> ⁂.</P>
<P>In meteorology, the therefore sign is used to indicate moderate rain on a <A href="/wiki/Station_model" title="Station model">station model</A>; the asterism indicates moderate snow.</P>
<P>To denote <A href="/wiki/Logical_implication" class="mw-redirect" title="Logical implication">logical implication</A> or <A href="/wiki/Entailment" class="mw-redirect" title="Entailment">entailment</A>, various signs are used in <A href="/wiki/Mathematical_logic" title="Mathematical logic">mathematical logic</A>: →, ⇒, ⊃, ⊢, ⊨. These symbols are then part of a mathematical formula, and are not considered to be punctuation. In contrast, the therefore sign is traditionally used as a punctuation mark, and does not form part of a logical formula.<SUP id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-3">[3]</A></SUP></P>
<P>The graphically identical sign ∴ serves as a <A href="/wiki/Japanese_map_symbol" class="mw-redirect" title="Japanese map symbol">Japanese map symbol</A> on the maps of the <A href="/wiki/Geographical_Survey_Institute_of_Japan" class="mw-redirect" title="Geographical Survey Institute of Japan">Geographical Survey Institute of Japan</A>, indicating a tea plantation. On other maps the sign, often with thicker dots, is sometimes used to signal the presence of a national monument or <A href="/wiki/Ruins" title="Ruins">ruins</A>.</P>
<P>The character ஃ in the <A href="/wiki/Tamil_script" title="Tamil script">Tamil script</A> represents the <A href="/wiki/%C4%80ytam" class="mw-redirect" title="Āytam">āytam</A>, a special sound of the <A href="/wiki/Tamil_language" title="Tamil language">Tamil language</A>.</P>
<P>In <A href="/wiki/Masonic" class="mw-redirect" title="Masonic">Masonic</A> traditions the symbol is used for <A href="/wiki/Abbreviation" title="Abbreviation">abbreviation</A>, instead of the usual period. For example "R∴W∴ John Smith" is an abbreviation for "Right Worshipful John Smith" (the term Right Worshipful is an archaic title just as "Land Lord" is and indicates that Brother Smith is a Grand Lodge officer).<SUP id="cite_ref-Mackey_4-0" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-Mackey-4">[4]</A></SUP></P>
<P>In <A href="/wiki/Norwegian_language" title="Norwegian language">Norwegian</A> and <A href="/wiki/Danish_language" title="Danish language">Danish</A>, a similar symbol is used as an explanatory symbol (<I>forklaringstegnet</I>). It can be typeset using the <A href="/wiki/Open_o" class="mw-redirect" title="Open o">open o</A> followed by a colon, thus: <B>ɔ:</B>. It is used for the meaning "namely", "id est", "scilicet" or similar<SUP id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><A href="#cite_note-5">[5]</A></SUP>.</P>
